ugh into different branches of it."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Father left her his three hour-glasses","body":"Because Susannah had already received her portion at marriage, Roger Newton Sr.'s 1683 will left her only one cow and all three of his hour-glasses. She was living in Guilford with five children at the time. The genealogical note adds dryly: 'No one can tell why she should have all the hour-glasses.'"},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Two marriages, six children, two Connecticut towns","body":"She had four children with her first husband John Stone, then married Samuel Burwell as his second wife. She was living in Guilford with five children when her father's 1683 will was written, then moved to Milford with the Burwells. She died at Milford in July 1703, age 48."}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"artworks":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Susannah Newton Burwell","first_name":"Susannah","last_name":"Burwell","married_names":["Stone","Burwell"],"maiden_name":"Newton"},"documents":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"susannah-burwell-1654"},"X00019":{"id":"X00019","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1660,"month":9,"day":22,"city":"Milford","county":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1722,"month":5,"day":31,"city":"Milford","county":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"X00024","date_year":1679,"location_city":"Milford","location_county":"New Haven","location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death","end_year":1691,"children_ids":["I00022"]},{"marriage_number":2,"spouse_id":"X00020","date_year":1689,"location_city":"Milford","location_county":"New Haven","location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death","end_year":1722,"children_ids":["I00019"]}],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entries 42, 54"}],"gender":"male","tags":["politician","king_philips_war"],"number_of_marriages":2,"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"politics","header":"Town Auditor, then fourteen sessions as Representative","body":"Zachariah Baldwin served as Auditor for the town of Milford in 1696, then as Representative in the Connecticut General Assembly for fourteen sessions between 1705 and 1718 — one of the more sustained civic careers among the Milford founding families' descendants."},{"number":2,"category":"religion","header":"Admitted to full communion","body":"In 1693, Zachariah and his second wife Elizabeth were admitted to full communion at First Congregational Church in Milford — the record noting that Zachariah was admitted \"having been forgiven in some unstated context.\" Whatever the transgression, it was significant enough to be recorded, and forgiven enough to be moved past."},{"number":3,"category":"military","header":"The Sergeant title — but which war?","body":"He is styled Sergt. in Milford records throughout his life. Born in 1660, he was 15 during King Philips War (1675-76) — possible but young; he was 29-37 during King Williams War (1689-97), the more likely conflict. The specific service remains unconfirmed in surviving records."}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"H00042","display_label":"Married my daughter Mary; his cousin married my daughter Susanna","link_text":"Thomas Newton"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"H00054","display_label":"Both Hooker-line grandsons married his daughters","link_text":"John Burwell"}],"military_service":[{"war":"King Williams War (probable) or King Philips War (possible)","rank":"Sergeant","side":"Colonial","battles":[]}],"bio":{"title":"Sergeant","display_name":"Sgt. Zachariah Baldwin","first_nam